011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RMB" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>25 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RMB" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>27 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RMB" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>3 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>4 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RMB" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, pilot 43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>12 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="REV" RESP="MKD" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>19 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><STANDARD>Knight, Ellis Cornelia</STANDARD><DIV1><PERSONNAME><DIV2><DATASTRUCT><DATAITEM><BIRTHNAME WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Knight, Ellis Cornelia"><GIVEN>Ellis</GIVEN><GIVEN>Cornelia</GIVEN><SURNAME>Knight</SURNAME></BIRTHNAME></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><INDEXED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Knight, E. Cornelia">E. Cornelia Knight</INDEXED></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><INDEXED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Knight, Miss">Miss Knight</INDEXED></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><INDEXED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Knight, Cornelia,,, Miss">Miss Cornelia Knight</INDEXED></DATAITEM></DATASTRUCT></DIV2></PERSONNAME></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Birth</HEADING><BIRTH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE>27 March 1757</DATE><CHRONPROSE><BIRTHPOSITION POSITION="ONLY"> ECK was born in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Westminster">Westminster</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, the only child of <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Sir Joseph,, d. 1771">Sir Joseph Knight</NAME> and his second wife, the former <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">Philippina Deane</NAME>.</BIRTHPOSITION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 17" DBREF="786">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Seventeen days later, on April 13, she was baptized in <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="St Margaret&apos;s Church,, Westminster">St Margaret&apos;s church</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Westminster"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> with her family in attendance.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 17" DBREF="786">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></BIRTH></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Throughout her life ECK associated with the highest <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="English">English</NATIONALITY> society, at first through connections of her father and later as a result of her years of royal service to <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME>. Her family lived a comfortable <CLASS SOCIALRANK="PROFESSIONAL" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">middle-class</CLASS> or <CLASS SOCIALRANK="GENTRY" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">genteel</CLASS> existence until the death of her father, when reduced financial circumstances forced her and her mother to go abroad in order to economize.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB " DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She was an <ORGNAME STANDARD="Anglican Church"><DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Anglican">Anglican</DENOMINATION></ORGNAME> and was presumably <RACECOLOUR>white</RACECOLOUR>.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Family and Familial Connections</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Mother</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK&apos;s mother, n&eacute;e <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">Philippina Deane</NAME>, was born in Essex on 17 November 1726. She was a descendant of <NAME STANDARD="Deane, Anthony,, 1638 - 1721">Sir Anthony Deane</NAME>, shipbuilder, naval officer, Fellow of the Royal Society, and associate of <NAME STANDARD="Pepys, Samuel">Samuel Pepys</NAME>. In 1679 he shared with Pepys the experience (while they were briefly Members of Parliament for Harwich) of being arrested on trumped-up charges which were then lifted the next year. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 21, 22" DBREF="786">21, 22</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wheatley xxxi, xxxiii" DBREF="69785">xxxi, xxxiii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Philippina Deane married Captain Joseph Knight on <DATE>18 December 1755</DATE>, when she was twenty-nine years old. It was Captain Knight&apos;s second marriage: he had lost his first wife (whose cause of death is not given). He had a son and two daughters with the first Mrs. Knight, but his son died while serving in the army. Captain Knight was concerned about having to leave two daughters at home while he was at sea. The logical solution was to marry again, and for his second match he chose Philippina Deane, who was young, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sprightly and sociable.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 22, 23" DBREF="786">22, 23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> ECK was close with her mother growing up and remained so throughout her life. In her autobiography, she describes her mother as possessing a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">great quickness of perception, wit, and vivacity, a happy facility in conversation, and a singular frankness of temper</QUOTE> and combining <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">warmth of heart with the keenest satirical penetration.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 24" DBREF="61467">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Father</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK&apos;s father, <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Sir Joseph,, d. 1771">Sir Joseph Knight</NAME>, was a <JOB REG="naval officer">Rear-Admiral</JOB> of the White squadron. He entered the <ORGNAME>Royal Navy</ORGNAME> at the age of fourteen, needing a profession since his family had lost a considerable amount of their landed property through their <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">attachment to the cause of royalty</QUOTE> during the reign of <NAME STANDARD="Charles I, King">Charles I</NAME>. He distinguished himself through his service to the navy and was knighted on board ship in Portsmouth by <NAME STANDARD="George III, King">King George III</NAME> during a royal naval review.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 6, 23" DBREF="61467">6, 23</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Sir Joseph died at Harwich on <DATE VALUE="1775-09-08">8 September, 1775</DATE>, a few months after he was promoted to the rank of Rear-Admiral.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 33, 34 n1" DBREF="61467">33, 34 n1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><DIV2><HEADING>Stepsiblings</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK had two stepsisters and a stepbrother from her father&apos;s previous marriage. Her stepbrother died young as a captain in the <ORGNAME>British Army</ORGNAME> before she was born.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight, 24" DBREF="61467">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><HEADING>Older Friends</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>During her childhood, ECK associated with a variety of celebrated people through her family connections. Her mother was a close friend of painter and writer <NAME>Frances Reynolds</NAME> (sister to the more famous painter <NAME STANDARD="Reynolds, Sir Joshua">Sir Joshua Reynolds</NAME>), and the family spent much time in their company. This connection brought ECK in contact with many well-established literary figures, such as <NAME>Samuel Johnson</NAME>, <NAME>Edmund Burke</NAME>, <NAME>Oliver Goldsmith</NAME>, <NAME>Elizabeth Montagu</NAME>, and <NAME STANDARD="Baretti, Giuseppe Marc&apos;Antonio">Giuseppe Baretti</NAME>. Her father&apos;s association with Dr Johnson began when Sir Joseph was in command of a ship called the <RS TYPE="ship">Ramillies</RS>. Johnson was curious about what it was like to live on a naval warship and therefore passed a week on board. The two men&apos;s friendship continued throughout ECK&apos;s life; after her father&apos;s death it was Johnson who wrote Lady Knight&apos;s petition for a pension and presented it to the king.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 6, 26, 27, 34" DBREF="61467">6, 26, 27, 34</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 33" DBREF="786">33</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Education</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK was well educated for her time and class. From the age of five she attended a <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="PRIVATE" STUDENTBODY="SINGLESEX" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="PRIMARY">boarding-school</SCHOOL> kept by four Swiss sisters in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">parlour day-boarder</QUOTE> three days a week. There she studied <SUBJECT>dancing</SUBJECT> and <SUBJECT>French</SUBJECT>.  <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 25" DBREF="61467">25</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION><EDUCATION MODE="DOMESTIC"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On the intermediate days she was privately educated at home in more <SUBJECT>French</SUBJECT> as well as in <SUBJECT>Latin</SUBJECT>, <SUBJECT>Greek</SUBJECT>, <SUBJECT>mathematics</SUBJECT>, <SUBJECT>geography</SUBJECT>, and <SUBJECT>history</SUBJECT>, by <INSTRUCTOR>M. Petitpierre</INSTRUCTOR>, a former pastor from Neufchatel. She later was taught <SUBJECT REG="dancing">dance</SUBJECT> by <INSTRUCTOR>Mr Novere</INSTRUCTOR>, a highly respected dancing master.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 25-26" DBREF="61467">25-26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Change in Fortune, Change in Location</HEADING><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After her father died in late 1775, while ECK and her mother were spending the winter in London, Lady Knight applied for a widow&apos;s pension from the Crown, in a petition drawn up by <NAME STANDARD="Johnson, Samuel">Dr Johnson</NAME>. But her petition was denied by Lord Sandwich,<RESEARCHNOTE>img: is it worth giving him a name tag? ljh: No name tag required, she doesn&apos;t come into contact w/him again.</RESEARCHNOTE> on grounds that she was not in dire circumstances.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 34" DBREF="61467">34</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Years Abroad</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><HEADING>Paris, Rome, Genoa</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>The newly-widowed Lady Knight was unable to obtain the house she had hoped for in London. For this reason and in an effort to economize, she and her daughter decided to go abroad. An invitation was extended to one of ECK&apos;s half-sisters, but she declined, preferring to stay in London.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 34" DBREF="61467">34</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATESTRUCT CERTAINTY="C" VALUE="1776-04-"><SEASON VALUE="4" CERTAINTY="C">Spring</SEASON> <YEAR VALUE="1776">1776</YEAR></DATESTRUCT><CHRONPROSE>ECK and her <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">mother</NAME> left <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England">England</GEOG></PLACE> with the intention of remaining abroad for three years. In the event their time abroad was eight times longer than that: it lasted until 1800.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 35" DBREF="61467">35</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>They first spent some time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, where a highlight of their stay was a sight of <NAME STANDARD="Louis XVI,, King of France">Louis XVI</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Marie-Antoinette,, Queen of France">Marie Antoinette</NAME> at the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Palace of Versailles</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Versailles"></SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 37" DBREF="61467">37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Leaving Paris, the Knight pair embarked for <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toulouse</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> and passed the winter there before settling in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On reaching <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, they paused in their peripatetic existence and lived there for just over eight years.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><HEADING>Naples, Southern France, Northern Italy</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>2 May 1785</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK and her <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">mother</NAME> left <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, where they had been living for some eight years, to travel south to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 41" DBREF="61467">41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Naples was then the capital of the <FOREIGN REG="old regime" LANG="fr">ancien-r&eacute;gime</FOREIGN> kingdom of Naples and Sicily (also known as the Two Sicilies), and they were presented there to its queen, <NAME STANDARD="Maria Carolina,, Queen of the Two Sicilies">Maria Carolina</NAME><RESEARCHNOTE>img to Mariana. Have used Two Sicilies in her standard name because we already have her husband in as King of the Two Sicilies (and the next generations) but please make sure that a version with Queen of Naples and Sicily goes in as alt form, and please do the same for her husband and descendants. Thanks!</RESEARCHNOTE>, whom ECK found to be less impressive than her younger sister<NAME STANDARD="Marie-Antoinette,, Queen of France"> Marie Antoinette</NAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 41" DBREF="61467">41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The Knights remained in Naples for about a year, until the latter part of <DATE>May 1786</DATE>, when they voyaged to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Marseilles</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>. ECK noted a change in manners in the French since their earlier time in that country, which she attributed in part to the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">revolutionary spirit</QUOTE> that had taken hold there. Scandalous reports regarding Marie Antoinette had begun to circulate, aimed at discrediting the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><FOREIGN REG="high society" LANG="fr">haute soci&eacute;t&eacute;</FOREIGN></QUOTE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 42" DBREF="61467">42</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When Knight and her mother left Naples they moved to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vienne</SETTLEMENT> in <GEOG REG="France">France</GEOG></PLACE>, where they stayed three years, until <DATE VALUE="1789-05-">May of 1789</DATE>. From there they proceeded to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Avignon</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="France" REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="Aix-en-Provence" REG="Aix-en-Provence">Aix-en-Provence</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toulon</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Nice</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Fr&eacute;jus</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Savona</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> (by way of the <PLACE><REGION REG="River Rhone">Rh&ocirc;ne</REGION><AREA REG="Europe"></AREA></PLACE>) on their way to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Genoa</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Italy" REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 42-3" DBREF="61467">42-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> During this tour of southern France and what is now northern Italy, ECK published her first novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dinarbas</TITLE>, a continuation of Samuel Johnson&apos;s famous <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rasselas</TITLE>, in 1790.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The Knights very much liked living in the trading republic of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Genoa</SETTLEMENT> (now but not then politically part of <GEOG REG="Italy">Italy</GEOG></PLACE>). But by the end of April 1791 they felt compelled to leave because, as ECK noted, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the intrigues of the revolutionary government of France rendered this city an undesirable residence for English families.</QUOTE> They therefore returned to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, where once again they remained settled for about seven years.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 44, 45" DBREF="61467">44, 45</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Rome Again</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1791-04-30">30 April 1791</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Having left Genoa for <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> on this day, ECK lived there with her <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">mother</NAME> through turbulent times until early 1798. They were there when in 1792 she published her second book, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Marcus Flaminius</TITLE>, set in ancient Rome.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 44, 45" DBREF="61467">44, 45</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>They arrived in Rome shortly after the revolutionary French government broke off relations with the Papacy. In <DATE>March 1791</DATE> ECK noted that a spirit of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">revolutionary propagandism</QUOTE> was fomenting rebellion against the Pope&apos;s rule in Rome and the Papal States (which were then fairly extensive). The following year France declared war on imperial Austria and other major European powers (on <DATE>20 April 1792</DATE>) and petitioned the Pope for formal diplomatic recognition. <SCHOLARNOTE><P>These dates are from the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Orlando</TITLE> textbase.</P></SCHOLARNOTE> The Pope refused to recognize any government in France except for that of the monarchy, and military tension escalated between revolutionary France and the Papacy. ECK notes in her diary that in the space of several days in <DATE VALUE="1793-01-" CERTAINTY="C">mid-January 1793</DATE> over three thousand Frenchmen fled from Rome.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 46, 47" DBREF="61467">46, 47</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> France invaded the Italian peninsula in spring 1796. ECK and her mother remained in Rome until some time in 1798, the year the French occupied the city. Then, not without difficulty, they made their escape, heading for <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, from which they later moved on to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Palermo</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sicily"></REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 99" DBREF="786">99</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK, like her mother, was <POLITICALAFFILIATION INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTYES">conservative</POLITICALAFFILIATION> by temperament and tradition, and a convinced <POLITICALAFFILIATION MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES">monarchist</POLITICALAFFILIATION>. It is ironic that having left Paris before the <POLITICALAFFILIATION INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTYES" REG="anti-revolutionary"><TOPIC>French Revolution</TOPIC>, which filled her with horror</POLITICALAFFILIATION>, she found her footsteps dogged by the international political unrest which the revolution aroused. <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, governed by the Papacy, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, capital of the kingdom on the Two Sicilies (or Naples and Sicily), were each bastions of the <FOREIGN REG="old regime" LANG="fr">ancien r&eacute;gime</FOREIGN>, but shaken during her stay or immediately after her departure by revolutionary wars which she found not only physically but also philosophically horrifying.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><HEADING>Royalty in Power and in Exile</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Wherever they went the Knights always met, and always admired, members of the relevant royal family. On a visit to the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Palace of Versailles</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Versailles"></SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE><RESEARCHNOTE>img: I see we have two Reg forms: Palace of Versailles and Chateau de Versailles. I believe the second is what it should be. ljh to img: palace of versaille is the english version and chateau is the french word for palace. used chateau in the attributes.</RESEARCHNOTE> during their time in Paris, they were able to see <NAME STANDARD="Louis XVI,, King of France">Louis XVI</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Marie-Antoinette,, Queen of France">Marie Antoinette</NAME> in the great gallery as they passed by on their way to chapel. ECK notes in her autobiography that she was struck by Marie Antoinette&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very pleasing smile</QUOTE> when she greeted her as she passed. Louis, she notes, appeared <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">grave and rather melancholy.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 37" DBREF="61467">37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> they met the King and Queen of Naples and Sicily, <NAME STANDARD="Ferdinand I,, King of the Two Sicilies">Ferdinand</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Maria Carolina,, Queen of the Two Sicilies">Maria Carolina</NAME>. Of this couple the queen was the political driving force, both while on the throne and after she had been driven out from Naples to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Palermo</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sicily"></REGION><GEOG CURRENT="Italy" REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, where the Knights met her again in internal exile.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 41" DBREF="61467">41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Meanwhile in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Italy" REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> (which was then home to many French aristocrats whose estates had been confiscated) ECK and her mother were introduced to <NAME STANDARD="Adelaide, Madame,, of France">Madame Adelaide</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Victoire, Madame,,, of France">Madame Victoire</NAME>, princesses of the French royal family, aunts to Louis XVI. Knight wrote that they were considered <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very courteous and affable</QUOTE> and that they were frequently petitioned by emigr&eacute;s in distress for financial aid. The princesses sold off their jewelry piece by piece in order to help their countrymen, and Knight reported that they were exceptionally well thought of by the Romans, both by the higher class and by the common people, who shared a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">horror</QUOTE> of the French revolution and had no great love for France in general.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 45, 46" DBREF="61467">45, 46</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Naples</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1798-02-" CERTAINTY="BY">Early 1798</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK and her <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">mother</NAME> fled from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Rome</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with some difficulty</QUOTE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> after the French invaded Rome in February and confiscated British property.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight, 48" DBREF="61467" QTDIN="QTDINYES">48</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell, 99" DBREF="786">99</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On their previous visit to Naples in 1785, the Knights had met <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Sir William,, 1731 - 1803">Sir William Hamilton</NAME>, the British ambassador there, as well as the rulers, <NAME STANDARD="Ferdinand I,, King of the Two Sicilies">Ferdinand</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Maria Carolina,, Queen of the Two Sicilies">Maria Carolina</NAME>. On their return to Naples they renewed their acquaintance with Sir William and met his wife, <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Emma,,, Lady">Emma, Lady Hamilton</NAME>. (At the time of their first visit, Hamilton had not yet remarried after the death of his first wife.) ECK and her mother were also introduced to <NAME STANDARD="Nelson, Horatio">Horatio Nelson</NAME>, who arrived in Naples on <DATE VALUE="1798-09-22">September 22, 1798</DATE>, fresh from his victory at the battle of the <PLACE><REGION REG="River Nile">Nile</REGION><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE> (or the battle of <PLACE><REGION>Aboukir Bay</REGION><GEOG REG="Egypt"></GEOG></PLACE>). It was during this time that ECK composed such a variety of poetry celebrating Nelson&apos;s victories that she was called his poet-laureate.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell, 77, 82, 100, 102, 104, 105" DBREF="786">77, 82, 100, 102, 104, 105</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Palermo</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE>1 January 1799</DATE><CHRONPROSE>After leaving <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Naples</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Italy" REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, where the tide of revolution had caught up with them again, ECK and her mother reached <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Palermo</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Sicily</REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>. They sailed through storms and high seas which took a toll on <NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">Lady Knight</NAME>&apos;s health.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 63" DBREF="61467">63</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>They fled from Naples, capital of the kingdom of Naples and Sicily or the Two Sicilies, at about the same time as its king. The royal family (<NAME STANDARD="Ferdinand I,, King of the Two Sicilies">Ferdinand</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Maria Carolina,, Queen of the Two Sicilies">Maria Carolina</NAME>) escaped from the invading French armies of the revolution under the protection of the British Navy and <NAME STANDARD="Nelson, Horatio">Lord Nelson</NAME>, while in Naples a short-lived French satellite Republic was established .<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 58-59" DBREF="61467">58-59</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Nelson" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In Palermo the Knights&apos; friendship with the Hamiltons and Nelson grew, and there Lady Knight died.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell, 114-116" DBREF="786">114-116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>20 July 1799</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Knight, Philippina,,, Lady">Lady Knight</NAME>, mother of ECK, died at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Palermo</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Sicily</REGION><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE> after suffering indifferent health for a long time.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 66" DBREF="61467">66</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I was deprived of her enlightened judgement for my protection and guidance, and of her animated and instructive conversation for my comfort and delight. She had sustained many trials with fortitude and dignity. Her mind was clear and penetrating, and her heart warm and generous.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 66" DBREF="61467" QTDIN="QTDINYES">66</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><HEADING>Back to England</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>6 November 1800</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK landed in <PLACE><REGION>Norfolk</REGION> after an absence from <GEOG REG="England">England</GEOG></PLACE> which had been planned as three years but had stretched to twenty-four.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 76" DBREF="61467">76</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>For a while she lived with <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Sir William,, 1731 - 1803">Sir William</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Emma,,, Lady">Lady Hamilton</NAME> after they rented a house in <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Grosvenor Square</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, from a friend.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 66, 78" DBREF="61467">66, 78</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Nelson and the Hamiltons</HEADING><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><LIVESWITH>As her mother had wished, once back in England ECK placed herself under the protection of powerful friends made abroad: <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Sir William,, 1731 - 1803">Sir William Hamilton</NAME> (British Ambassador to the court of the Two Sicilies), his wife <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Emma,,, Lady">Emma, Lady Hamilton</NAME>, and the young naval officer recently created <NAME STANDARD="Nelson, Horatio">Lord Nelson</NAME>. Nelson, already a local hero because of his victories over the French, had master-minded the escape of the court, including the Hamiltons, from Naples to Sicily, where they had arrived just a week before the Knights.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 66" DBREF="61467">66</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Nelson" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></LIVESWITH> He continued to be a frequent guest of the Hamiltons and there was already much public speculation as to the nature of his relationship with Lady Hamilton, although at this time the gossip from Naples and Palermo had not yet reached England. ECK was beginning to be aware that she was in a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">vulnerable position</QUOTE> because of her association with the possibly culpable Emma. The growth of scandalous rumours <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">plunged her [ECK] into a conflicting state of embarrassment and gratitute.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 116" DBREF="786">116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It seems that she only slowly and unwillingly admitted that an adulterous affair was in progress. She wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I must say that there was certainly at that time no impropriety in living under Lady Hamilton&apos;s roof. Her house was the resort of the best company of all nations, and the attentions paid to Lord Nelson appeared perfectly natural. He himself always spoke of his wife with the greatest affection and respect; and I remember that, shortly after the battle of the Nile, when my mother said to him that no doubt he considered the day of that victory as the happiest in his life, he answered, <QUOTE DIRECT="N">No; the happiest was that on which I married Lady Nelson.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 66" DBREF="61467">66</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>This, of course, was relatively early in his acquaintance with Emma Hamilton.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></QUOTE></P><P>The rumours continued to plague all those concerned after the Hamiltons and Nelson returned to England (by which time, in fact, <NAME STANDARD="Hamilton, Emma,,, Lady">Emma Hamilton</NAME> was pregnant by <NAME STANDARD="Nelson, Horatio">Nelson</NAME>). <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 78" DBREF="61467">78</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Nelson" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> ECK mentions dining with the foursome of the Hamiltons and the Nelsons in the former&apos;s rented London house, where plans were made to attend the theatre the following evening. She declined the invitation, but recorded that <NAME STANDARD="Nelson, Frances,,, Viscountess">Lady Nelson</NAME> fainted in the box. Many of Knight&apos;s friends were pressing her to give up the acquaintance, but she feared incurring the charge of ingratitude, especially after the Hamiltons&apos; kindness to her at the time her mother died. She mentions being <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">greatly embarrassed</QUOTE>, as she felt that things had become <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very unpleasant</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 78" DBREF="61467">78</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and that Nelson&apos;s irritation at the scandal caused him to dote on Lady Hamilton all the more, which made matters worse. Finally (just as Emma bore their baby in secret) he received a posting as second in command of the Baltic fleet.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Nelson" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Before he left he wrote to his wife, Lady Nelson, approving her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">perfectly moral conduct</QUOTE> but announcing that he would not live with her any more.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 78-79" DBREF="61467">78-79</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> ECK never admits to witnessing any improper behaviour, but it is clear that the scandal caused her distress. It may have made her subsequent appointment in the Queen&apos;s court all the more enticing.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Windsor</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><HEADING>Lady of the Bedchamber to Queen Charlotte</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>March 1805</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Aylesbury, Anne Elizabeth Brudenell-Bruce,,, Countess of">Lady Aylesbury or Ailesbury</NAME>, a senior lady of the bedchamber to <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz,, Queen of England">Queen Charlotte</NAME>, informed ECK of the queen&apos;s desire for her too to be <JOB REG="courtier">employed at court</JOB>, without specific duties other than that of <JOB REG="lady of the bedchamber">attendance on the queen</JOB>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight, 82" DBREF="61467">82</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK notes that she was to reside at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Windsor</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Berkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in a house belonging to her Majesty <REMUNERATION>and she would be provided three hundred pounds a year as well as a servant for her house.</REMUNERATION> Her duties were largely social: she was required to attend on the Queen on various mornings and to be present at her evening parties when invited. She was to be available on Sundays and all red-letter days should the Queen require her company, yet she was to absent herself on visits to friends when her services were not needed, particularly when their Majesties removed to Weymouth where they spent two to three months every summer.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 82" DBREF="61467">82</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> ECK gratefully accepted the position and notes that she was honoured by it and that it was entirely unsolicited on her part.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1805-12-" CERTAINTY="BY">By December 1805</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK, in her new position as lady of the bedchamber to <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz,, Queen of England">Queen Charlotte</NAME>, became a resident of <PLACE><PLACENAME>Windsor Castle</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Windsor"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Berkshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 83" DBREF="61467">83</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>The <EMPLOYER><NAME STANDARD="Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz,, Queen of England">Queen</NAME></EMPLOYER> would call on her each morning on her way to <PLACE><PLACENAME>Frogmore</PLACENAME>, her house in <SETTLEMENT>Windsor</SETTLEMENT>&apos;s <REGION REG="Windsor Park">Home Park</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 83 n1" DBREF="61467">83 n1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The Queen was fond of being read aloud to in either French, English, or German, and because ECK was fluent in ten languages she was a perfect <JOB>companion</JOB> in this regard. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight, 83" DBREF="61467">83</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The Princesses <NAME STANDARD="Gloucester, Mary,,, Duchess of">Mary</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth, Princess,, 1770 - 1840">Elizabeth<RESEARCHNOTE>img to Mariana: she&apos;s mentioned in several other docs, and will need an alternative version of her name in the auth list: Hesse-Homburg, Elizabeth,,, Landgravine of</RESEARCHNOTE></NAME> would frequently join their mother and ECK for walks in the garden, whereas Princesses <NAME STANDARD="Augusta Sophia, Princess">Augusta</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Sophia, Princess">Sophia</NAME> preferred to ride with their father, the king. During this time, ECK became especially close to <NAME STANDARD="Amelia, Princess,, 1783 - 1810">Princess Amelia</NAME>, whose illness and subsequent death in 1810 she took particularly hard.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 83" DBREF="61467">83</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 144" DBREF="786">144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She did some inventive <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">writing and publishing</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> during these years, too: <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="teacher">sets of cards for teaching European history</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, contributions to collections of poems, and translating hymns and prayers from the original German.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell, 148" DBREF="786">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Lady Companion to the Princess</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE>January 1813</DATE><CHRONPROSE>At the request of the Prince Regent (later <NAME STANDARD="George IV, King">George IV</NAME>), and the urgings of the princesses <NAME STANDARD="Gloucester, Mary,,, Duchess of">Mary</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth, Princess,, 1770 - 1840">Elizabeth</NAME>, and <NAME STANDARD="Sophia, Princess">Sophia</NAME>, ECK agreed to serve as one of the <JOB REG="companion">lady companions</JOB> to the seventeen-year-old <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME> (their niece).</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 104, 106, 110, 112" DBREF="61467">104,106, 110, 112</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK&apos;s transfer of her services to Princess Charlotte (the Regent&apos;s only child) was not favoured by the <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz,, Queen of England">Queen</NAME> (Princess Charlotte&apos;s grandmother), who wished to retain ECK in her current position. In her autobiography Knight admits, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I could not find it in my heart to devote myself till death to the Queen&apos;s service, sacrificing the pleasing idea of rendering happy the life of a persecuted young creature.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 108" DBREF="61467">108</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Later, however, she came to regret her decision to leave the Queen&apos;s service. She commented that in deciding she had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">consulted my feelings more than my reason.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 213" DBREF="61467">213</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Her decision to accept this new position strained her relationship with the Queen, whose letter written in reply to her acceptance she found to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">resentful and bitter to a high degree</QUOTE> and by which she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hurt beyond expression.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 111" DBREF="61467">111</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Although she wrote to the Queen a few days later conveying her regret at any offence given, she did not receive a reply.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 112" DBREF="61467">112</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </P><P>ECK&apos;s position as a lady companion to <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME> was complicated by the intention of the princess&apos;s father, <EMPLOYER><NAME STANDARD="George IV, King">the Regent</NAME></EMPLOYER>, to keep his daughter <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as long as possible <EMPH>a child</EMPH>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 114" DBREF="61467">114</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> While subject to the Regent&apos;s wishes, ECK later commented in notes, probably written during the 1830s, that: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I had the romantic desire that Princess Charlotte should think for herself, and think wisely.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 157" DBREF="786">157</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>When the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Morning Chronicle</TITLE> announced on <DATE VALUE="1813-01-30">January 30</DATE> her appointment as a <JOB REG="governess">sub-governess</JOB>, ECK insisted on having the claim contradicted, as she was not a sub-governess but a lady companion to the Princess. This insistence on her status surfaced again in a letter written to the Prince Regent in <DATE VALUE="1813-04-">April</DATE>, in which she complained of her treatment since arriving at Windsor, specifically the Queen&apos;s reference to her as a sub-governess.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 117, 129-130" DBREF="61467">117,129-130</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK&apos;s desire that the <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">princess</NAME> (eventual heir to the throne) should learn to think for herself, allied her with the hope of the nation (perhaps especially strong among women) that the princess would prove both wise and virtuous as a ruler, that she would lead a national renaissance and <POLITICALAFFILIATION WOMAN-GENDERISSUE="GENDERYES" MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES" REG="monarchist">redeem the currently abysmal reputation of the monarchy</POLITICALAFFILIATION>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 213" DBREF="61467">213</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><HEADING>Fall from Favour</HEADING><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE>12 July 1814</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK was dismissed from the <JOB REG="companion">service</JOB> of <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME>, the month after the princess had broken off her engagement to <NAME STANDARD="William II,, King of the Netherlands">William, Prince of Orange</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 186" DBREF="61467">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The <EMPLOYER><NAME STANDARD="George IV, King">Regent</NAME></EMPLOYER> made no complaint about ECK at her dismissal, but it would appear that the dismissal was related to Princess Charlotte&apos;s decision that she would not marry a prince who seemed likely to subordinate the interests of Britain to those of his own country, the Netherlands. She could hardly, she felt, be queen regnant of Britain while largely absent abroad.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Princess Charlotte" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 189" DBREF="786">189</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Previous incidents related to the princess&apos;s conduct may also have played a role in Knight&apos;s dismissal. Rumours in the summer of 1813 which linked the princess&apos;s name with that of the <NAME STANDARD="Cavendish, William George Spencer,,, sixth Duke of">Duke of Devonshire</NAME> (son of <NAME STANDARD="Devonshire, Georgiana Cavendish,,, Duchess of">Georgiana, Duchess of Devonshire</NAME>) resulted in reprimands to both ECK and the <NAME STANDARD="Leeds, Catherine Osborne,,, Duchess of">Duchess of Leeds</NAME> for their conduct.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 140" DBREF="61467">140</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> ECK claimed, however, that these rumours were <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">false reports, or exaggerated statements.</QUOTE>  <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 141" DBREF="61467">141</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Princess Charlotte refused to re-consider the Dutch alliance, and said so in a letter to her father sent on July 9. ECK commented in her autobiography that after the lettter was sent: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">We heard various reports of the intentions of the Regent: it was said that I and the servants were to be dismissed.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 175" DBREF="61467">175</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> On July 11 Knight had an audience with the Regent, in which she found him <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very cold, very bitter, and very silent,</QUOTE> and concerned about visits paid to Princess Charlotte by <NAME STANDARD="Augustus, Frederick William Henry,, Prince of Prussia">Prince Augustus of Prussia</NAME>&mdash;who, it was rumoured, was married <FOREIGN REG="left-handed marriage" LANG="fr">de la main gauche</FOREIGN>. The following day ECK was dismissed. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 175-177" DBREF="61467">175-177</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Prince Augustus, an army officer, was nearly twenty years older than Princess Charlotte. He never married, but had children by two successive long-term non-marital relationships.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK remained in London after her dismissal in order to be able to contradict any untrue reports that might surface in the press. It was during this time that she agreed to pass letters between <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Augustus, Frederick William Henry,, Prince of Prussia">Prince Augustus</NAME>. She continued to act as messenger between them until Princess Charlotte, finally convinced that Augustus had no serious intentions of marrying her, ended the correspondence in January.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 193-194" DBREF="786">193-194</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Travel</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1816--">Spring 1816</DATE><CHRONPROSE> ECK left for a holiday in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>. She returned to <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> in <DATE VALUE="1816-07-">July</DATE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 199" DBREF="786">199</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 210" DBREF="61467">210</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After her return she paid several visits to <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta, Princess">Princess Charlotte</NAME>, who was by now married to <NAME STANDARD="Leopold I,, King of Belgium">Prince Leopold of Saxe-Coburg</NAME>. These visits were brief, however, and Prince Leopold made it clear that he did not welcome them.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 199-200" DBREF="786">199-200</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK then left <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and spent the late summer and autumn touring through <PLACE><REGION>Essex</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><REGION>Huntingdonshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. Her next few years were filled with travel in Europe. She toured in <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE> from the spring of 1817 until her return to England in May 1819. She left England again in 1821 for <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, where she stayed three years, and cultivated acquaintances such as the <NAME STANDARD="Angoul&ecirc;me, Marie-Th&eacute;r&egrave;se-Charlotte,,, duchesse d&apos;">duchesse d&apos;Angoul&ecirc;me</NAME> and the <NAME STANDARD="Orl&eacute;ans, Louise-Marie-Ad&eacute;la&iuml;de de Bourbon,,, duchesse d&apos;">duchesse d&apos;Orl&eacute;ans</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 199-200, 202-206" DBREF="786">199-200, 202-206</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Knight 211" DBREF="61467">211</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>During these three years spent in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, from 1821 to 1824, ECK began to think of that, rather than England, as her home.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1824 ECK visited <PLACE><GEOG>Germany</GEOG></PLACE> at the invitation of <NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth, Princess,, 1770 - 1840">Princess Elizabeth<RESEARCHNOTE>img to Mariana: she&apos;s mentioned in several other docs, and will need an alternative version of her name in the auth list: Hesse-Homburg, Elizabeth,,, Landgravine of</RESEARCHNOTE></NAME>, one of George III&apos;s daughters who in 1818 had married <NAME STANDARD="Hesse-Homburg, Leopold Viktor Friedrich,,, Landgrave of">Prince Friedrich</NAME> (later Friedrich VI, Landgrave of Hesse Homburg). ECK also met on this visit Elizabeth&apos;s sister, the former Princess Royal, now <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta Matilda,, Princess Royal">Queen Dowager of W&uuml;rtemberg</NAME>, who took an immediate liking to her. From <DATERANGE FROM="1825--" TO="1828--" EXACT="BOTH">1825 to 1828</DATERANGE>, ECK divided her time between <PLACE><GEOG>Germany</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>. The death of the Queen Dowager of W&uuml;rtemberg on <DATE>6 October 1828</DATE> affected her deeply, and after spending the winter in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Stuttgart</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Germany"></GEOG></PLACE> she left for <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 206-207, 209, 213-215" DBREF="786">206-207, 209, 213-215</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Having spent three years in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>, from 1821 to 1824, and begun to regard that, rather than England, as her home, ECK returned there on <DATE VALUE="1830-08-15">August 15, 1830</DATE>, but she did not stay long. Angry and unsettled by the overthrow of <NAME STANDARD="Charles X,, King of France">Charles X</NAME> and the establishment of the new regime under <NAME STANDARD="Louis-Philippe,, King of France">King Louis-Philippe</NAME>, she left for England, arriving in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Dover</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Kent"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> on <DATE VALUE="1830-09-09">September 9th</DATE>. Once back in England she turned again to writing, the product of which was a historical novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Sir Guy de Lusignan</TITLE>, published in <DATE>1833</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 216-217" DBREF="786">216-217</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>ECK continued through the later part of her life to cultivate relationships with royalty and the aristocracy, of her own nation and others. Her friendships with <NAME STANDARD="St Vincent, John Jervis,,, Earl of">Lord St Vincent</NAME> and with <NAME STANDARD="Aylesbury, Anne Elizabeth Brudenell-Bruce,,, Countess of">Lady Aylesbury (or Ailesbury)</NAME> were particularly close. She remained on good terms for many years with several of George III&apos;s daughters: <NAME STANDARD="Elizabeth, Princess,, 1770 - 1840">Princess Elizabeth</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Augusta Sophia, Princess">Princess Augusta</NAME>, and the former <NAME STANDARD="Charlotte Augusta Matilda,, Princess Royal">Princess Royal (Charlotte, who became Queen and then Queen Dowager of W&uuml;rtemberg)<RESEARCHNOTE>img to mariana: she too will need an alternative form: Charlotte,, Queen of W&uuml;temberg</RESEARCHNOTE></NAME>. After her move to Paris in 1821, she continued to circulate in high society. Among her acquaintances there were intellectuals such as <NAME STANDARD="Denon, Dominique-Vivant,,, baron">Dominique-Vivan Denon</NAME> the Egyptologist, <NAME STANDARD="Humboldt, Friedrich Heinrich Alexander von">Alexander von Humboldt</NAME> the scientist, and <NAME STANDARD="Sta&euml;l, Germaine de">Madame de Sta&euml;l</NAME> the woman of letters. Also among them were royalty and partners of royalty, such as the <NAME STANDARD="Angoul&ecirc;me, Marie-Th&eacute;r&egrave;se-Charlotte,,, duchesse d&apos;">duchesse d&apos;Angoul&ecirc;me</NAME> (daughter of the executed Louis XVI) and the <NAME STANDARD="Orl&eacute;ans, Louise-Marie-Ad&eacute;la&iuml;de de Bourbon,,, duchesse d&apos;">duchesse d&apos;Orl&eacute;ans</NAME> (widow of the executed <SOCALLED>Philippe Egalit&eacute;</SOCALLED>), the <NAME STANDARD="Charles X,, King of France">comte d&apos;Artois</NAME> (later Charles X), the <NAME STANDARD="Gontaut, Marie-Josephine-Louise,,, duchesse de">duchesse de Gontaut</NAME>, the <NAME STANDARD="Narbonne, Fran&ccedil;oise de Chalus,,, duchesse de">duchesse de Narbonne</NAME>, the <NAME STANDARD="Cayla, Zo&eacute; Talon,,, comtesse du">comtesse du Cayla</NAME> (mistress of Louis XVIII), the <NAME STANDARD="Boufflers, El&eacute;onore de Jean,,, marquise de">comtesse de Boufflers (formerly de Sabran)<RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: I did some further research on the comtesse de Boufflers and she is actually Eleonore de Jean de Manville, Comtesse de Sabran (First marriage to Joseph Comte de Sabran) She later married Jean, Chevalier de Boufflers ). img: I think we have the right standard now. Mariana, can you list <SOCALLED>Sabran, El&eacute;onore de Jean,,, comtesse de</SOCALLED> as alternative form? I suppose she was really comtesse, not yet marquise, when ECK met her, but if ECK is wrong at least we have the right standard!</RESEARCHNOTE></NAME>, and her son <NAME>Elz&eacute;ar de Sabran</NAME>.<RESEARCHNOTE>img: are you right about this one? the only person of this name I can find is a medieval saint! kgl: according to Luttrell, he is the son of the comtesse de Boufflers by her first marriage.  img: ok.</RESEARCHNOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 204-206 210-211, 214" DBREF="786">204-206 210-211, 214</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Though the author, wit, and clergyman <NAME>Sydney Smith</NAME> described ECK as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a very disagreeable affected woman, living up two pairs of stairs  and looking very ugly,</QUOTE> the novelist <NAME STANDARD="Bury, Lady Charlotte">Lady Charlotte Bury</NAME> mentioned that she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the most high-minded women in the world, and the kindest-hearted.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 211, 214" DBREF="786">211, 214</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Living up two flights of stairs would indicate comparative poverty.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Death</HEADING><DEATH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1837-12-17" CERTAINTY="UNKNOWN">17 December 1837 or soon afterwards</DATE><CHRONPROSE>ECK  died in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> of an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><CAUSE>inflammation of the Lungs</CAUSE>.</QUOTE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Luttrell 221" DBREF="786" QTDIN="QTDINYES">221</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Sources differ as to her death date. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of Naional Biography</TITLE> gives it as 17 December. Her biographer <NAME>Barbara Luttrell</NAME> quotes a doctor saying she died on the 18th, while herself dating the death as two weeks after Knight fell ill and three months short of her eightieth birthday, which would put it a couple of days later still.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></DEATH></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE></SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></BIOGRAPHY>